            <h3>General</h3>
        <ul class="wa-faq" data-faq="faq">
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">Am I billed separately for local disk storage?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No. All new virtual machines have an operating system disk and a local disk (or resource disk). We do not charge for local disk storage. The operating system disk is charged at the regular rate for disks. <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn197896.aspx">See all virtual machines configurations</a></p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">If my deployed instance says &quot;stopped, am I still getting billed?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>Maybe. If the status says Stopped (Deallocated), you are not being billed. If it says Stopped Allocated, you are still being billed for allocated virtual cores (not the software license itself). Full details on VM states are available <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn763934.aspx">here</a>.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>State</th>
<th>Billed</th>
<th>Details</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Starting</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td>The initial starting state of VMs as they are going through the boot cycle. This period is billed as the VMs are running.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Running (Started)</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td>The running state of the VM.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Stopped</td>
<td>Yes</td>
<td><p>You are billed for Allocated cores, but not software license.</p><p>Note: To put a VM in Stopped status, use the power option within the VM, not from the Azure management portal.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Stopped (Deallocated)</td>
<td>No</td>
<td><p>Cores are no longer allocated to the VM and are no longer billed.</p><p>Note: To put a VM in Stopped (Deallocated) status, use the Shutdown option from the Azure management portal.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">Does the virtual machine instance price include storage costs associated with the running image?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No, it doesnt.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">If my virtual machine ran for less than an hour, how much do I get billed?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>We charge for the number of minutes your virtual machine is running, rounded to the nearest minute, not hour.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">What is internal load balancing?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>It is a new preview feature for Azure Virtual Machines with private IP addresses. The internally load balanced endpoint is only accessible within a virtual network (for VMs within a VNET) or cloud service (for VMs outside a VNET). Internal load balancing is useful for multi-tier applications where some of the application tiers arent public facing yet require load balancing functionality.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">How can I check that I have properly stopped a VM and that I am not being billed for it?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>You can check the status of your virtual machines in the Virtual Machines tab and also in the VM Dashboard. If VM status says "Stopped," you are still being billed. Only "Stopped (Deallocated)" indicates you are not billed.</p>
<p>To ensure you are not being billed, always stop virtual machines from the management portal. You can also stop the VM through Powershell by calling ShutdownRoleOperation with "PostShutdownAction" equal to "StoppedDeallocated".</p>
<p>If you shut down a VM from inside ( using Windows power options) or through PowerShell by calling ShutdownRoleOperation with "PostShutdownAction" equal to "Stopped".</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">How are various instance sizes billed?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>All hours for A0, A2, A3 and A4 sizes are converted into A1 (small) instance hours when presented on your bill. <a href="/en-in/pricing/faq/virtual-machines-how-do-instance-sizes-get-billed/">Learn More</a></p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">If I have instances in two different regions, how am I charged for data transfers?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>Each instance is charged for its data egress across regions.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">Is tax included in the pricing above?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No. Tax will be added separately.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
        </ul>
            <h3>Windows Server</h3>
        <ul class="wa-faq" data-faq="faq">
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">If I upload my on-premises Windows Server image to Azure, do I need to provide my license keys?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No. Microsoft provides the Windows Server license keys for any running instances.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">If I download an Azure Windows Server image to my datacenter, is the license transferrable?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No. You will need to supply a license for the image.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
        </ul>
            <h3>Oracle Software</h3>
        <ul class="wa-faq" data-faq="faq">
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">Can I use my 30-day free trial credits to purchase Oracle software?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No, you cannot. If you want to use Oracle software during your trial, you need to turn off the default 

<span class="price-data" data-amount="0">$0</span> <a href="/en-in/pricing/spending-limits/">spending limit feature</a> and pay regular pay-as-you-go rates. <strong>Otherwise you will hit your spending limit and your subscription will be immediately disabled</strong>.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">Can I use my MSDN, Bizspark, or MPN credits to pay for Oracle software?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>No, these Azure credits do not apply. To buy Oracle software, you will need to turn off the default 

<span class="price-data" data-amount="0">$0</span> <a href="/en-in/pricing/spending-limits/">spending limit feature</a> and pay regular pay-as-you-go rates. <strong>Otherwise, you will hit your spending limit and your subscription will be immediately disabled</strong>.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
        </ul>
            <h3>SQL Server</h3>
        <ul class="wa-faq" data-faq="faq">
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">When would I use Azure SQL database vs. SQL Server?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>If you have existing applications or workloads you simply want to grab and move to the cloud or extend parts of on-premises application to the cloud, SQL Server in a Virtual Machine is the easiest option. If you are looking to build new relational applications, SQL Database is probably the best long-term solution. Either way, Azure makes it easy to move applications back and forth between an on-site datacenter and the cloud as business needs change.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">Which edition of SQL Server 2014 should I pick?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>To help you choose, <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/cc645993.aspx">here is a detailed feature comparison</a>.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">What is different about the data warehousing edition of SQL Server enterprise?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>Data warehousing is typically a complex workload to setup, configure and tune. The specially optimised data warehouse image for Azure Virtual Machines improves performance for these workloads by as much as 20 percent over the regular SQL Server Enterprise virtual machine image. <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn387396.aspx">How it works</a></p>
                    </div>
                </li>
        </ul>
            <h3>SharePoint</h3>
        <ul class="wa-faq" data-faq="faq">
                <li class="wa-faq-question">
                    <a href="#">I already have a SharePoint license. Can I use it for Azure?</a>
                    <div class="wa-faq-answer">
                        <p>It depends. You can use your license if you meet the requirements for <a href="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=624378">License Mobility through Software Assurance</a> or have a <a href="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=626646">Services Provider License Agreement (SPLA)</a>.</p>
                    </div>
                </li>
        </ul>
</div>

